# [[you]]; [[ye]]: [[second person|second-person]] plural pronoun

====Usage notes====
In Louisiana French and Quebec French, where the use of {{m|fr|vous}} is generally very restricted, this is the usual form of the second-person plural pronoun, corresponding to Southern American English {{m|en|y'all}}. 

In Louisiana, despite being always plural in meaning, ''vous-autres'' is used with third-person singular forms of the verb to form statements and questions:
: {{uxi|fr|'''Vous-autres''' est trop de bonne heure.|'''Y'all''' are too early.}}
: {{uxi|fr|'''Vous-autres''' veut boire du pop ou quelque chose?|Do '''y'all''' want to drink some pop or something?}}
In commands, the verb takes the same endings as for ''vous'' and the reflexive pronoun is ''vous-autres'':
: {{uxi|fr|Coupez '''vous-autres''' pas!|Don't cut '''yourselves'''!}}
Otherwise (with singular verbs), the reflexive pronoun {{m|fr|se}} is used:
: {{uxi|fr|'''Vous-autres''' se rappelle de ça?|Do '''y'all''' remember that?}}

